    <fr:title text="Exercises about hom-sets of modules">Exercises about hom-sets of modules</fr:title>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be a ring.</html:p>
    <html:ol><html:li>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X\in \mathop {\mathrm {Mat}}\nolimits _{n}(R)]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix with entries in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>. If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\det (X)\neq 0]]></fr:tex>, then is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> invertible as a matrix? (Does <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\det (X)]]></fr:tex> even make sense if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is noncommutative?)</html:li>
<html:li>For any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m,n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R^{m}\cong  R^{n}]]></fr:tex> as modules, then is it true that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m=n]]></fr:tex>?</html:li>
<html:li>Does the notion of a <fr:link href="/vectsp-000T/" title="Basis of vector space" uri="http://localhost:8000/vectsp-000T/" display-uri="vectsp-000T" type="local">"basis"</fr:link> carry over to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R^{n}]]></fr:tex>?</html:li></html:ol>
  </fr:mainmatter>
